{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608048"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:29:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:29:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15981"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15981"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72857"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8672"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58327"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20762"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72857"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, several cavities and membranes form in a specific spatial arrangement. These structures include the chorionic cavity, amniotic cavity, and yolk sac, which are separated by distinct tissue layers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is found between the chorionic cavity and the definitive yolk sac at week two of embryonic development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extraembryonic mesoderm","Syncytiotrophoblast","Primary yolk sac","Cytotrophoblast","Amniotic cavity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the spatial arrangement of embryonic structures is precisely organised. \u003Cstrong\u003EExtraembryonic mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E fills the space between the chorionic cavity and the definitive yolk sac during week two of development. This mesoderm is crucial for the formation of blood vessels and supporting structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eamniotic cavity\u003C/strong\u003E develops above the embryonic disc. It will later surround the developing embryo and contain amniotic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary yolk sac\u003C/strong\u003E is present earlier in development but is replaced by the definitive yolk sac by the end of week two. It cannot, therefore, be found between these structures at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecytotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esyncytiotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E are components of the developing placenta, forming the outer layers of the developing embryo. They are not found in the space between the chorionic cavity and definitive yolk sac.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these spatial relationships is crucial for comprehending normal embryonic development and potential developmental abnormalities. The extraembryonic mesoderm will go on to form important supporting structures including blood vessels that connect the chorion and yolk sac.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The extraembryonic mesoderm fills the space between the chorionic cavity and definitive yolk sac during early embryonic development.","Understanding the spatial relationships of early embryonic structures is crucial for comprehending normal development and potential abnormalities."],"references":["Rehman B, Muzio MR. Embryology, Week 2-3. [Updated 